 nuclear power capacity by 2050, adding 200 gigawatts through new reactors,=
 plant restarts, and upgrades. In addition, the plan calls for 35 gigawatts=
 of new capacity within a decade. </p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This is one of the =
most ambitious plans for nuclear energy ever laid out by a U.S. president &=
#8212; instead of maintaining the status quo or focusing entirely on safety=
 concerns, the plan meets bipartisan momentum for nuclear energy, which has=
 been pulled forward by the AI boom and other geopolitical issues. Nuclear =
buildout has stagnated for the last 50+ years, with barely any capacity add=
ed since the 90s. This plan flips that with a goal to not only increase nuc=
lear capacity, but triple it within 25 years. </p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>T=
he plan itself is pretty on point. Joe must&#8217;ve been a </span><em><a h=
ref=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/0a6514a3-119e-49ca-8921-0ec74cff9e2c?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Age of Miracles</=
a></em><span> listener. The plan calls for capacity expansion through the c=
onstruction of new sites and the revival of idle plants, the deployment of =
